<PageTitle>
    Core Rules - Wealth
</PageTitle>

<h1>Wealth</h1>

<br />

<MudText Typo="@Typo.body1">
    Deedforge uses abstraction of Wealth in order to circumvent the hassle of counting your coins.
    <br /><br />
    Each character can have one of 15 levels of Wealth. Each Wealth Level represents increasing financial "security" 
    of the character, thus allowing them to spend money on increasing number of necessities, items and services 
    without having to worry about becoming destitute.
</MudText>

<br />
<br />

<MudText Typo="@Typo.h5">Expenses</MudText>
<br />
<MudText Typo="@Typo.body1">
    Anything that costs money to obtain is called an Expense. All Expenses have a cost express with Wealth Level. 
    If an Expense has a cost that is below Wealth Tier of a character, then it is considered to be a Minor Expense. 
    Otherwise, it is considered to be a Major Expense.
</MudText>

<br />
<br />

<MudGrid Spacing="4" Justify="Justify.SpaceEvenly">
    <MudItem xs="4">
        <MudText Typo="@Typo.h5">Minor Expenses</MudText>
        <br />
        <MudText Typo="@Typo.body1">
            Everyday expenses like food, lodging, and basic supplies that wouldn't decrease the wealth level but are assumed 
            to be covered by it, assuming character's level of Wealth is sufficiently high for a particular Minor Expense.
            <br /><br />
            When purchasing a Minor Expense, character's level of Wealth does not change.
        </MudText>
    </MudItem>
    <MudItem xs="4">
        <MudText Typo="@Typo.h5">Major Expenses</MudText>
        <br />
        <MudText Typo="@Typo.body1">
            Purchasing property, rare items, or other significant assets would decrease your wealth level by one or more tiers.
            <br /><br />
            When purchasing a Major Expense, character's Wealth goes down a number of Wealth Levels equal to the cost 
            of the bought item or service.
        </MudText>
    </MudItem>
</MudGrid>

<br />
<br />

<MudText Typo="@Typo.h5">Wealth Tiers</MudText>
<br />
<MudText Typo="@Typo.body1">
    Levels of Wealth are split based on Wealth Tiers, which are used to denote whether an Expense is a Minor 
    or a Major Expense.
</MudText>

